{
  "text": "(S p ) Remark 1. A less demanding notion of \"geometric subadditivity\" could be introduced by requiring the above inequality only when the multisets X i ∪ Y i lie in disjoint parallelepipeds (see [CITATION_1] where such a notion is used in order to encompass more complicated single sample functionals). It is clear from the proofs that some of our results hold assuming only geometric subadditivity (upper limit for bounded absolutely continuous laws for example). We will not push this idea further in this paper.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "118410816"
  },
